It is proposed to redevelop a portion of the existing Daytona Plaza shopping center
located at the northwest corner of the intersection of International Speedway Boulevard
& Clyde Morris Boulevard in the City of Daytona Beach, Florida. The proposed
redevelopment project is anticipated to be completed by the end of 2014. The site
location is illustrated in Figure 1. The following modifications are being proposed for
the shopping center as part of the redevelopment project:
Demolition of 7,144 square feet of fast-food rest. w/ drive-through use
Construction of 2,676 square feet of general commercial use
Construction of 5,171 square feet of fast-food rest. w/ drive-through use
Construction of 1,651 square feet of coffee shop w/ drive-through use
A copy of the site plan can be found in the Appendix.
Kimley-Horn and Associates, Inc. was retained to evaluate the traffic impacts
associated with the proposed redevelopment. This analysis was conducted in
accordance with the Volusia Transportation Planning Organization’s (TPO)
Transportation Impact Analysis Guidelines document and the traffic methodology
letter (dated January 15, 2013) that was approved by City staff. A copy of the
methodology letter is included in the Appendix.
The data used in this analysis was obtained from the City of Daytona Beach and the
Florida Department of Transportation (FDOT). Additionally, Kimley-Horn and
Associates, Inc. collected other relevant data including intersection turning movement
Trip generation calculations for the proposed redevelopment were based upon rates

page.text: An evaluation of which roadways and intersections are impacted by the proposed
redevelopment was prepared based on thresholds established in the Volusia TPO’s
Transportation Impact Analysis Guidelines document. According to this document, if
a project generates less than 100 two-way peak hour external trips, then all roadways
where the project’s peak hour trips consume one percent (1%) or more of that
roadway’s generalized service volume shall be analyzed. The proposed redevelopment
meets this criterion. AM peak hour and PM peak hour significance calculations are

Background traffic is comprised of existing traffic and ambient growth in traffic
between the current year and the buildout year.
Existing traffic volumes were based on intersection turning movement counts collected
in March of 2013. All raw traffic count data can be found in the Appendix.
To account for ambient growth in traffic between the count year (2013) and the
proposed buildout year of 2014, it was necessary to review historical Annual Average
Daily Traffic (AADT) data from count stations within the base study area. Historical
AADT data was obtained from the Florida Department of Transportation and a
negative “area-wide” annual growth rate was calculated (-0.82%). While the historical
AADT volumes indicated a negative growth rate, per City guidelines, a 2% growth rate
was applied in order to provide for a more conservative analysis. Growth rate
calculations and AADT data can be found in the Appendix.
A review of the Five-Year Capital Improvement Plans (CIPs) of the City of Daytona
Beach, Volusia County, and the Florida Department of Transportation was performed
to determine if there are any roadway capacity improvements in the transportation study
area. No improvements within the study area were found.
A capacity analysis was undertaken for the adjacent roadway segments which the
project has direct connections to considering their projected total traffic volumes and
the roadway laneage to be in place in 2014. For the purposes of this analysis, total
traffic is defined as the sum of existing traffic, ambient traffic growth, and project
traffic. The increase in PM peak hour trips associated with the proposed
redevelopment is nominal. Therefore, as agreed to in the methodology, the capacity
analysis was limited to AM peak hour conditions. Projected 2014 total traffic
conditions are detailed in Table 4 for peak season AM peak hour two-way conditions.
The capacity standards for each roadway during peak hour conditions were obtained
from the Florida Department of Transportation 2009 Quality/Level of Service

Per the approved traffic methodology, the following intersections were analyzed for
AM peak hour conditions based on existing traffic conditions, background traffic
conditions (without project) in the year 2014, and total traffic conditions (with project)
International Speedway Blvd & Clyde Morris Blvd
AM peak hour turning movement counts were performed at the above mentioned
intersections in March of 2013. A two percent (2%) growth rate was applied to the
intersection volumes to account for ambient traffic growth. Project traffic was then
added to obtain 2014 total traffic volumes. Intersection volume development sheets are
provided in the Appendix. Intersection analyses were conducted using Highway
Capacity Software 2010 software, which is based upon the methodologies contained in
the Highway Capacity Manual. The results of the intersection analyses are summarized
in Table 5 for existing traffic conditions, 2014 background (without project) traffic
conditions, and 2014 total (with project) traffic conditions.

In the AM peak hour, the project is anticipated to generate between 100 and 300
two-way external trips. Therefore, AM peak hour impacted roads will include all
roadways where the project’s peak hour trips consume three percent (3%) or
more of a roadway’s 2-way peak hour generalized service volume based on the
In the PM peak hour, the project is anticipated to generate less than 100 two-way
external trips. Therefore, PM peak hour impacted roads will include all
roadways where the project’s peak hour trips consume one percent (1%) or more
of a roadway’s 2-way peak hour generalized service volume based on the
Impacted roads will be evaluated for conformance to their respective level of
service standards. Furthermore, intersections along any impacted roadways will
be evaluated using Highway Capacity Software. Should any capacity
deficiencies exist, the TIA will include mitigation improvements. Coordination
with the City will occur when developing mitigation options.
The estimated buildout year for the project is 2014.
Should any roadways/intersections be found to be impacted by the project, they
will be studied under the following scenarios:
2014 – with project traffic and mitigation (if necessary)
Should any traffic count data collection be necessary, we will first coordinate
with the City to utilize any available data within the past year. If no data is
available, we will collect necessary segment count data (48 hours) and necessary
intersection turning movement count data during the AM peak hour (7am to 9am)
and the PM peak hour (4pm to 6pm).
An area-wide background growth rate was calculated utilizing historical AADT
data obtained from the FDOT 2011 Traffic Information database. The
background growth rate that was calculated was -0.82%. These growth rate
calculations are attached to this letter in the form of a summary sheet.
While the historical AADT volumes indicate a negative growth rate, per City
